The paper deals with binary search trees (BSTs) and their rotations, which are fundamental data structures in computer science, and hence it is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. The paper also establishes connections between BSTs and rectangulations, which are well-studied combinatorial objects in computational geometry, and hence it is likely to belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) category. The paper also discusses the flip-sequence between two rectangulations, which is a well-known problem in discrete mathematics, and hence it is likely to belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) category. The paper also applies transformations to the obtained geometric model, which is a common technique in graph theory, and hence it is likely to belong to the cs.GT (Graph Theory) category. Finally, the paper discusses the dynamic optimality conjecture of Sleator and Tarjan, which is a well-known open problem in theoretical computer science, and hence it is likely to belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) category.
